{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480021"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:35:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:35:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"3"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/3"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.08,0.03,0.2,0.59]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"3"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112243"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/3"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"3"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94308"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"82"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31593"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31594"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37575"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41951"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46010"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112243"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of palpitations. She has no chest pain, shortness of breath, or dizziness. She has a history of Graves disease and takes carbimazole and propranolol. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 180/min, blood pressure 150/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She is alert and oriented. Her ECG shows a regular narrow complex tachycardia at 180/min (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Synchronised cardioversion","Intravenous metoprolol","Intravenous flecainide","Intravenous adenosine","Vagal stimulation manoeuvre"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a regular narrow complex tachycardia consistent with supraventricular tachycardia (SVT). She is haemodynamically stable with normal blood pressure and no signs of compromised end-organ perfusion. Vagal manouevres should first be attempted - cold water immersion and forceful coughing is no longer recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E vagal stimulation manoeuvre\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step as it is non-invasive, safe, and can be effective in terminating SVT. Traditionally this was done by carotid sinus massage. This works by stimulating vagal tone, which slows conduction through the atrioventricular node. This should be performed with the patient supine for less than five seconds while monitoring the ECG. Care must be taken with this procedure and it undertaken gently. If there is any history suggestive of carotid artery disease, this procedure should be avoided. The modified valsalva manoeuvre is now more often preferred. This is done by asking the patient to forcibly exhale for 15 seconds against some form of resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous adenosine\u003C/strong\u003E would be the next step if carotid sinus massage is unsuccessful. While effective, it causes transient asystole and significant patient discomfort, so vagal manoeuvres should be attempted first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynchronised cardioversion\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for patients who are haemodynamically unstable with signs of shock, severe hypotension, or acute heart failure. This patient is stable and therefore does not require immediate electrical cardioversion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous metoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered for rate control but is not first-line therapy for acute termination of SVT. The patient is already taking oral propranolol, and additional beta-blockade may not be beneficial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous flecainide\u003C/strong\u003E is a class IC antiarrhythmic that can be used for chemical cardioversion of SVT, but it is not first-line therapy and carries risks of pro-arrhythmia. It would only be considered after simpler interventions have failed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carotid sinus massage is first-line management for stable supraventricular tachycardia","Assessment of haemodynamic stability through vital signs and end-organ perfusion is critical in tachycardia","Regular narrow complex tachycardia with sudden onset suggests paroxysmal supraventricular tachycardia"],"references":["Mahtani AU, Nair DG. Supraventricular Tachycardia. Med Clin N AM 2019; 103:863-79. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31378331/","The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. Modified Valsalva manoeuvre for supraventricular tachycardia. In: Handbook of Non-Drug Interventions (HANDI). Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/handi/handi-interventions/procedures/modified-valsalva-manoeuvre-for-supraventricular-tachycardia","Brugada J, Katritsis DG, Arbelo E, Arribas F, Bax JJ, Blomstr\u00f6m-Lundqvist C, et al. 2019 ESC Guidelines for the Management of Patients with Supraventricular tachycardiaThe Task Force for the Management of Patients with Supraventricular Tachycardia of the European Society of Cardiology (ESC). European Heart Journal. 2019 Aug 31;41(5).  Available at: https://academic.oup.com/eurheartj/article/41/5/655/5556821"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94308"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"3"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19890"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19890"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/38fe62f6-0169-42f0-b279-737dd6fb21df.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/38fe62f6-0169-42f0-b279-737dd6fb21df.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":388}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94308"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-26T20:33:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-26T20:34:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"3"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112243"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"typ